@hsu000001 To the extent that you are looking to model real-world “things”, I think an ontology or controlled vocabulary would be the best place to start. 2/3

@hsu000001 An #ontology is just a more expressive version of a #data model — a continuum in what you can express about the model. ER is slightly less expressive than UML, which is somewhat less expressive than OWL. Of course, that’s an oversimplification, but works. 1/3

The ENVO ontology and many others from the OBO foundry express many earth science concepts in OWL.
The COR (community ontology repository) from ESIP contains many earth science related ontology models, including the SWEET model. 2/2 #datahelpdesk #AGU20

From @metamattj: Data models are easily represented as UML (Unified Modeling Language) or ER (Entity Relationship) diagrams, & as ontologies using, ex. OWL (web ontology language). The ISO19115 family of metadata standards expresses metadata models for the geosciences in UML. 1/2 https://t.co/Y5hgizGm9U
